In **Java** by default an array of `int`s is filled with zeros. You can use this to check if the array is fully filled. For example you can create a method which checks for 0 and returns true if there are no 0:

    public static bool isArrayFilled(int[] array) {
        for(int i = array.length; i &gt;= 0; i--){
            if(array[i] == 0) {
                return false;
            }
         }
         return true;
    }

If array is big enough and filled out of order, you can use [advanced algorithms][1] to find at least one 0 value in the array.


  [1]: https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/searching-algorithms/

Per my previous comment, you can share this array with another thread so that one thread can fill the values and another can check the array at the same time. When the second thread finds that there are no default values (or 0s) then it can notify the first thread (or the main thread). Here is how you can do that 

